            <!-- Educational content -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this heart rate calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool combines several evidence‑based formulas to estimate
                your maximum heart rate (HR<sub>max</sub>) and then builds 5
                training zones either as a percentage of HR<sub>max</sub> or
                using the Karvonen heart rate reserve (HRR) method.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Maximum heart rate formulas</h3>
              <p>We support multiple commonly used formulas:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fox (classic):</strong> \( HR_{max} = 220 - \text{age}
                  \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tanaka:</strong> \( HR_{max} = 208 - 0.7 \times
                  \text{age} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Gulati (women):</strong> \( HR_{max} = 206 - 0.88
                  \times \text{age} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Nes:</strong> \( HR_{max} = 211 - 0.64 \times
                  \text{age} \)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you choose “Average of all formulas”, the calculator computes
                each applicable formula (Gulati only if you selected female) and
                averages the results to smooth out differences.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Heart rate reserve &amp; Karvonen formula</h3>
              <p>
                Heart rate reserve (HRR) is the difference between your maximum
                and resting heart rate:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">\( HRR = HR_{max} - HR_{rest} \)</div>
              <p>The Karvonen method then sets a training target as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( HR_{target} = HR_{rest} + (HRR \times \text{intensity
                fraction}) \)
              </div>
              <p>For example, at 70% intensity:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( HR_{target} = HR_{rest} + 0.70 \times (HR_{max} - HR_{rest})
                \)
              </div>

              <h3>3. Standard 5 training zones</h3>
              <p>By default, the calculator uses these approximate ranges:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Zone 1 – Very easy:</strong> 50–60% (recovery,
                  warm‑up)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Zone 2 – Easy aerobic:</strong> 60–70% (endurance, fat
                  oxidation)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Zone 3 – Moderate:</strong> 70–80% (tempo,
                  “comfortably hard”)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Zone 4 – Hard:</strong> 80–90% (threshold, intervals)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Zone 5 – Very hard:</strong> 90–100% (VO<sub>2</sub>
                  max efforts)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                You can switch to a Polar‑style set or define your own custom %
                ranges if you follow a specific training plan.
              </p>

              <h2>How to measure your resting heart rate</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Rest quietly for at least 5 minutes (ideally after waking,
                  before caffeine).
                </li>
                <li>Find your pulse at your wrist or neck.</li>
                <li>
                  Count beats for 30 seconds and multiply by 2 (or count for 60
                  seconds).
                </li>
                <li>Repeat on 2–3 mornings and take the average.</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                A lower resting heart rate generally indicates better
                cardiovascular fitness, but very low or very high values can
                sometimes signal medical issues.
              </p>

              <h2>Typical heart rate zones &amp; training goals</h2>
              <p>
                The table below summarizes how each zone is often used in
                training:
              </p>
              <table>
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th>Zone</th>
                    <th>Effort</th>
                    <th>Typical duration</th>
                    <th>Main benefits</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td>Zone 1</td>
                    <td>Very easy, can chat easily</td>
                    <td>Warm‑ups, cool‑downs, active recovery</td>
                    <td>Recovery, circulation, low stress</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>Zone 2</td>
                    <td>Easy, steady, nose‑breathing</td>
                    <td>30–120+ minutes</td>
                    <td>Aerobic base, fat metabolism, endurance</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>Zone 3</td>
                    <td>Moderate, conversation in short phrases</td>
                    <td>20–60 minutes</td>
                    <td>Cardio fitness, tempo runs, sustained efforts</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>Zone 4</td>
                    <td>Hard, talking is difficult</td>
                    <td>3–10 minute intervals</td>
                    <td>Lactate threshold, speed endurance</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td>Zone 5</td>
                    <td>Very hard, near all‑out</td>
                    <td>30 seconds–3 minutes</td>
                    <td>
                      VO<sub>2</sub> max, peak power, race finishing speed
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <h2>Limitations &amp; safety</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Formulas provide estimates and can be off by 10–15 bpm for
                  individuals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Medications (especially beta‑blockers) and conditions like
                  arrhythmias affect heart rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Perceived exertion (how hard it feels) is as important as
                  numbers on a watch.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you have heart disease, diabetes, chest pain, or other risk
                  factors, seek medical advice before high‑intensity training.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                <strong
                  >This calculator is for educational and fitness planning
                  purposes only and is not a medical device.</strong
                >
              </p>
            </section>

